  {
    "_creationTime": 1774946184675.9346,
    "_id": "jn70p4rpq0w2pkxw2p9hx10t2x83yhxd",
    "createdBy": "kd795pd2q713d3q8q22z5d4a7s822ec0",
    "description": "The data model is precise: requirements, sources, resolutions, rules. These are engineering terms that enable a clean implementation. But the product person never sees these words.\n\nThe surface language mapping:\n- 'requirement' → 'problem' (in discovery), 'area' (in refinement), unnamed/just-the-statement (in active/implemented) — as the artifact matures, it needs less labeling because its purpose is self-evident from its content\n- 'source' → 'evidence' — the thing that proves a problem exists or a behavior is needed\n- 'resolution' → 'decision' or 'proposed map edit' (when in review) — the thing someone decided and why\n- 'rule' → 'behavior' — the concrete thing the product does as a result of a decision\n\nThe key insight from the 'problem = requirement in discovery' resolution: the surface language hides the data model. A product person types 'checkout is confusing and we lose people at payment.' The system creates a discovery-status requirement. The product person sees: their problem statement, in their words, with an agent exploring it. They never see 'Requirement REQ-001 created. Status: Discovery.'\n\nAs the artifact matures:\n- Discovery: the artifact looks rough, personal, in the user's voice. The visual treatment is loose — maybe a handwritten-feeling font or less structured layout. It communicates: this is a thought, not a spec.\n- Refinement: the artifact has been explored. It has sub-problems, evidence, proposed structure. The visual treatment tightens — more structured, clearer connections, but still evolving. It communicates: this is taking shape.\n- Active: the artifact is well-defined. It has rules, traceability, dense connections. The visual treatment is clean and precise. It communicates: this is decided and being built.\n\nThe maturity of the CONTAINER matches the maturity of the THOUGHT. You don't put a sketch in a gilded frame. You don't put a blueprint on a napkin. The visual treatment adapts.\n\nThe transition is seamless. The product person never experiences a 'status change.' They experience their rough problem gradually becoming a precise specification as exploration and decisions accumulate. The object grows up in place.\n\nThis has implications for every UI surface:\n- The review queue shows 'Proposed decision' not 'Draft resolution'\n- The thread shows 'Field notes' not 'Thread messages'\n- The detail page shows 'Evidence' not 'Source references'\n- The canvas labels show the artifact's own statement, not a type label\n- The approval action says 'Approve this decision' not 'Approve resolution'\n\nOne exception: the CLI. Engineers and agents interact through the data model directly. 'statesman provenance requirements create' is correct for the CLI. The surface language is a product layer, not a data layer. The CLI speaks the data model. The web speaks the product language.",
    "projectId": "9887a770-ff7d-44d4-aeeb-a9c7b2252b73",
    "sourceRefs": [],
    "statement": "The product person's vocabulary in Provenance shall be problems, evidence, decisions, and behaviors — never requirements, sources, resolutions, and rules — with the surface language adapting to the artifact's maturity stage so that a rough problem described in natural language and a refined behavioral specification are experienced as the same object at different stages of understanding",
