    "createdBy": "kd795pd2q713d3q8q22z5d4a7s822ec0",
    "description": "When an agent determines that action is needed — creating requirements, drafting rules, changing artifact status — it proposes a draft resolution instead of acting directly. The resolution schema already has the right fields (title, context, position, rationale, enforcement, confidence). All six are mandatory at creation time. No partial drafts. No placeholder resolutions.\n\nThe agent's judgment about WHEN to propose a resolution vs. post a field note follows a simple heuristic: if the analysis implies something should be CREATED, CHANGED, or REMOVED in the graph, propose a resolution. If the analysis adds understanding without implying action, post a thread message.\n\nThe resolution title should be a clear statement of the proposed action (e.g., 'Create three sub-requirements decomposing checkout flow'). The context captures what the agent observed. The position captures what the agent recommends. The rationale captures why. The confidence (0.0-1.0) signals how certain the agent is. The enforcement classification (regulatory/policy/specification) signals what kind of change this represents.\n\nThe resolution MUST be linked to at least one parent requirement via a 'resolves' edge at creation time. Orphan resolutions — resolutions that address nothing — are structurally invalid. The resolution exists to resolve something.\n\nCreated by: Steve Jobs (agent: resolution workflow decomposition)",
    "projectId": "9887a770-ff7d-44d4-aeeb-a9c7b2252b73",
    "sourceRefs": [],
    "statement": "Agents shall propose draft resolutions by providing title, context, position, rationale, confidence, and enforcement classification, with all six fields mandatory at creation time",
